{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MXmnViT8Xwa9ebHFa4DYg3","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Testing\n     2→\n     3→All testing — local and CI — runs through `tests/run-scenarios.sh`.\n     4→\n     5→## Local Testing\n     6→\n     7→```bash\n     8→# Everything (shellcheck + all scenario fixtures)\n     9→tests/run-scenarios.sh\n    10→\n    11→# Filter to one agent\n    12→tests/run-scenarios.sh cargo-agent\n    13→\n    14→# Just shellcheck\n    15→tests/run-scenarios.sh shellcheck\n    16→\n    17→# List available scenarios\n    18→tests/run-scenarios.sh --list\n    19→```\n    20→\n    21→**Prerequisites**: `shellcheck` is required (`brew install shellcheck`).\n    22→Each scenario declares its own tool requirements in `REQUIRED_TOOLS` — if a\n    23→tool is missing, that scenario is skipped.\n    24→\n    25→## Shellcheck\n    26→\n    27→All shell scripts are linted with `shellcheck --severity=warning`. This runs:\n    28→\n    29→- Locally as the first check in `tests/run-scenarios.sh` (fails if shellcheck\n    30→  is not installed).\n    31→- In CI as a dedicated job.\n    32→\n    33→## Scenario Fixtures\n    34→\n    35→Each agent has fixture projects under `tests/<agent>/` that exercise known\n    36→pass and fail paths. See `docs/agents/scenario-tests.md` for the full\n    37→`scenario.env` contract and directory layout.\n    38→\n    39→At minimum every agent needs:\n    40→\n    41→- `tests/<name>-agent/clean/` — expects exit `0` (everything passes)\n    42→- `tests/<name>-agent/issues/` — expects exit `1` (intentional failures)\n    43→\n    44→## CI Workflow\n    45→\n    46→GitHub Actions runs on every push to `main` and on all pull requests\n    47→(`.github/workflows/ci.yml`).\n    48→\n    49→### Jobs\n    50→\n    51→| Job | What it does |\n    52→|-----|-------------|\n    53→| **shellcheck** | Lints all scripts with `--severity=warning` |\n    54→| **cargo-agent (baseline)** | Rust toolchain only, `USE_NEXTEST=0` |\n    55→| **cargo-agent (with-nextest)** | Adds `cargo-nextest`, `USE_NEXTEST=auto` |\n    56→| **npm-agent** | Node 22 |\n    57→| **terra-agent (baseline)** | Terraform only |\n    58→| **terra-agent (with-tflint)** | Adds tflint |\n    59→\n    60→All matrix jobs use `fail-fast: false` so every combination runs regardless\n    61→of individual failures.\n    62→\n    63→### Design Principles\n    64→\n    65→- **Test with and without optional tools** — matrix variants install optional\n    66→  dependencies (nextest, tflint) so we verify both the happy path and the\n    67→  graceful-skip path.\n    68→- **Same runner locally and in CI** — CI calls the same\n    69→  `tests/run-scenarios.sh` that developers run locally. No separate test\n    70→  harness.\n    71→- **CI-aware behaviour** — agents detect `CI=true` and adapt (unlimited\n    72→  `MAX_LINES`, check-only formatting). The workflow sets this env var\n    73→  explicitly.\n    74→\n    75→### Adding CI Coverage for a New Agent\n    76→\n    77→1. Add `clean` and `issues` scenario fixtures (see above).\n    78→2. Add a new job block to `.github/workflows/ci.yml`.\n    79→3. If the agent has optional tools, use a matrix to test with and without them.\n    80→4. The job should install required tools and call\n    81→   `tests/run-scenarios.sh <agent-name>`.\n    82→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01UaaUozJ2uL6jqxkwRdUpW4","session_id":"46dcc7a2-447a-40b5-b7b3-893789d3fd2e","uuid":"ebaa442d-0da3-4bc9-8048-9e1117b7e614"}
