f any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema\n- [ ] 14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS","newString":"- [x] 1. Read Spec 08 plus shared-library and refactor specs to confirm contract boundaries and integration points.\n- [x] 2. Inspect existing docker-related discovery/execution patterns in kube-agent, gha-agent, helm-agent, and install/README conventions.\n- [x] 3. Create `skills/docker-agent/scripts/docker-agent.sh` with shared-lib sourcing, env knobs, helper structure, and CLI parser.\n- [x] 4. Implement Dockerfile discovery that supports both repo-wide recursion and `CHANGED_FILES` filtering, with clear skip behavior.\n- [x] 5. Implement `lint` step with per-file `hadolint` execution, aggregate full diagnostics log, and `print_result` formatting.\n- [x] 6. Implement `build-check` step with opt-in `RUN_BUILD_CHECK`, optional `docker` detection, and `docker build --check -f <dockerfile> .` semantics.\n- [x] 7. Implement command dispatch (`lint`, `build-check`, `all`) with `RUN_*` gating and `--fail-fast` handling.\n- [x] 8. Add/extend test scenarios for `clean`, `issues`, and scoped/empty `CHANGED_FILES` behavior under `tests/docker-agent/`.\n- [x] 9. Add `skills/docker-agent/SKILL.md` with triggers, usage, and allowed-tools for all knobs including `RUN_BUILD_CHECK` and optional `TMPDIR_ROOT`.\n- [x] 10. Update `install.sh` to include `docker-agent` in `SKILLS`, dependency checks, and AGENTS/CLAUDE snippet output.\n- [x] 11. Update `README.md` with docker-agent in the table and usage examples.\n- [x] 12. Run `ralph validate plan` and fix any format/structure violations.\n- [x] 13. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema\n- [x] 14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS","originalFile":"## Implementation Checklist\n- [ ] 1. Read Spec 08 plus shared-library and refactor specs to confirm contract boundaries and integration points.\n- [ ] 2. Inspect existing docker-related discovery/execution patterns in kube-agent, gha-agent, helm-agent, and install/README conventions.\n- [ ] 3. Create `skills/docker-agent/scripts/docker-agent.sh` with shared-lib sourcing, env knobs, helper structure, and CLI parser.\n- [ ] 4. Implement Dockerfile discovery that supports both repo-wide recursion and `CHANGED_FILES` filtering, with clear skip behavior.\n- [ ] 5. Implement `lint` step with per-file `hadolint` execution, aggregate full diagnostics log, and `print_result` formatting.\n- [ ] 6. Implement `build-check` step with opt-in `RUN_BUILD_CHECK`, optional `docker` detection, and `docker build --check -f <dockerfile> .` semantics.\n- [ ] 7. Implement command dispatch (`lint`, `build-check`, `all`) with `RUN_*` gating and `--fail-fast` handling.\n- [ ] 8. Add/extend test scenarios for `clean`, `issues`, and scoped/empty `CHANGED_FILES` behavior under `tests/docker-agent/`.\n- [ ] 9. Add `skills/docker-agent/SKILL.md` with triggers, usage, and allowed-tools for all knobs including `RUN_BUILD_CHECK` and optional `TMPDIR_ROOT`.\n- [ ] 10. Update `install.sh` to include `docker-agent` in `SKILLS`, dependency checks, and AGENTS/CLAUDE snippet output.\n- [ ] 11. Update `README.md` with docker-agent in the table and usage examples.\n- [ ] 12. Run `ralph validate plan` and fix any format/structure violations.\n- [ ] 13. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema\n- [ ] 14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS\n\n## Architecture Review\n\n### System Design and Boundaries\n- `docker-agent` is a thin orchestrator over local tools and discovery logic: it accepts CLI/env inputs, normalizes scope, runs one or more steps, and emits standardized output.\n- Universal components come from `lib/x-agent-common.sh`.\n- Agent-specific logic lives entirely in `skills/docker-agent/scripts/docker-agent.sh` and covers: knob defaults, discovery, two checks, output orchestration, and command routing.\n- Metadata and integration points are external: `tests/run-scenarios.sh` (fixtures), `install.sh` (installation & discovery), and `README.md` / SKILL.md (operator contracts).\n\n### Dependency Graph and Coupling\n- Hard dependency: `hadolint` for `lint`.\n- Optional dependency: `docker` for `build-check`.\n- Runtime coupling: `CHANGED_FILES` and `RUN_*` are passed through environment and used in discovery/gating.\n- Shared-lib coupling: any changes to `x-agent-common.sh` (especially `print_result`, `setup_outdir`, `setup_lock`, `need`) directly affect all agents.\n- Installer coupling: missing `docker-agent` in `SKILLS` and dependency checks blocks user discoverability and installation behavior.\n\n### Data Flow and Bottlenecks\n- Data flow: Scenario/env → agent bootstrap → candidate discovery → per-step command execution → logs → structured step output → final exit code.\n- Main bottlenecks are filesystem scans (`find`) and external command execution cost.\n- `all` path is bounded by number of discovered Dockerfiles because each file runs one hadolint command (and one build-check command when enabled).\n\n### Scaling and Single Points of Failure\n- Largest scaling cost appears in broad repository scans; limit recursion to required extensions and exclude common non-project directories as in existing agents.\n- Single points: missing `hadolint`, missing `docker` (for build-check), permissions/access on target repository, and lock file contention across concurrent runs.\n- `setup_lock` in shared lib reduces run collisions but does not avoid tool contention (`docker`/`hadolint` runtime limits).\n\n### Security Architecture\n- No remote auth/API integration in docker-agent.\n- External command execution surface is restricted to shelling out to configured binaries using repository-local file paths from discovery.\n- Risk controls: consistent quoting, controlled candidate lists, and explicit scope filters reduce untrusted path expansion.\n\n### Key Architectural Decisions\n\nDecision 1: discovery strategy\n- Option A (recommended): `find` recursion with explicit prune patterns and `case`/globs for Dockerfile names.\n  - Effort: low, matches existing style. Risk: large trees still scanned.\n- Option B: use `git ls-files` first and filter tracked files.\n  - Effort: medium; misses untracked temporary fixture files and is inconsistent with other agents.\n- Option C: delegate discovery to external index tool.\n  - Effort: high and extra dependency; anti-pattern for this repo.\n- Chosen: Option A.\n- Implication: straightforward integration with existing patterns and no new dependency risk.\n\nDecision 2: build-check scheduling\n- Option A (default): include `build-check` only when `RUN_BUILD_CHECK=1` and not in clean default `all` path.\n  - Effort: minimal and aligns with FRs.\n- Option B: always run build-check in `all`.\n  - Effort low but slow/expensive and can fail due environment.\n- Option C: run build-check as part of `all` only when `docker` available.\n  - Better defaults than B but still unexpectedly heavy.\n- Chosen: Option A.\n- Implication: prevents expensive defaults while keeping opt-in explicit.\n\nDecision 3: logging granularity\n- Option A (recommended): per-file command outputs appended to one step log, with summary `print_result` and truncated stdout.\n  - Effort: medium; clear evidence and easy log discovery.\n- Option B: one log file per file.\n  - Effort high with cleanup/path noise.\n- Option C: stream only final output, no full logs.\n  - Effort low but weak diagnostics and rework-heavy.\n- Chosen: Option A.\n- Implication: keeps logs searchable and consistent with existing agents.\n\n### Future Impact\n- Decision choices preserve shared patterns used by upcoming 09/10 agents.\n- `CHANGED_FILES` semantics and scoped fixture expectations should be reused as default for other discovery-based new agents.\n- Explicit optional-step behavior (default-off `RUN_BUILD_CHECK`) sets a precedent for expensive operations in later agents.\n\n## Code Quality Planning\n\n### Organization and Module Structure\n- Keep one script file under `skills/docker-agent/scripts/` with small helper functions.\n- Maintain one-step-per-function structure: `discover_dockerfiles`, `run_lint`, `run_build_check`.\n- Use `LIB_DIR` + shared-lib sourcing exactly once; avoid duplicating lock/cleanup/parsing helpers.\n\n### DRY Opportunities and Reuse\n- `step`, `fmt_elapsed`, `need`, `print_result`, `setup_outdir`, `setup_lock`, `print_overall` from common lib.\n- Reuse `RUN_*` pattern and `should_continue` pattern from `all` command.\n- Reuse discovery pattern style from `gha-agent` for `CHANGED_FILES` filtering.\n- Avoid introducing new local utility duplicates for printing `Result/Time` that bypass common helpers.\n\n### Error Handling and Edge Cases (explicit)\n- Required tool missing (`hadolint`): fail fast with exit 2, clear install guidance.\n- Optional `docker` missing while `RUN_BUILD_CHECK=1` or `build-check` command invoked: emit `Result: SKIP (docker not found)` for that step and continue with non-fatal semantics in scoped contexts.\n- No Dockerfiles discovered: emit explicit `Result: SKIP` and treat as success.\n- `CHANGED_FILES` set but no matches: skip with `Result: SKIP` and return success.\n- `CHANGED_FILES` contains paths to non-Dockerfile entries: ignore safely.\n- `docker build --check` exits non-zero for a file: fail step and continue aggregation.\n- Log directory handling: rely on `setup_outdir` for cleanup semantics.\n\n### Engineering Level and Maintainability\n- Prefer predictable, explicit loops over compact one-liners to reduce shell ambiguity.\n- Keep output messages deterministic and aligned with existing contract.\n- Keep `docker-agent.sh` under ~200 LOC of domain-specific code by delegating boilerplate to the shared library.\n- Add comments for decision-sensitive behavior (`RUN_BUILD_CHECK` default OFF, optional skip).\n\n### Technical Debt Controls\n- Document assumptions for expensive operations and file-globbing semantics in `SKILL.md` and script `usage()`.\n- Keep scenario coverage close to FR requirements to prevent silent regressions (especially scope + skip branches).\n\n## Test Strategy\n\n### Coverage Scope\n- Smoke/e2e: `tests/run-scenarios.sh docker-agent` (fixture-based).\n- Contract tests for install/README consistency by manual inspection or explicit command checks in work plan run.\n- Shell lint: `shellcheck --severity=warning` via scenario harness.\n\n### Scenario Plan\n- `tests/docker-agent/clean/` with valid Dockerfile and `REQUIRED_TOOLS=\"hadolint\"` should pass.\n- `tests/docker-agent/issues/` with hadolint violations should fail.\n- Add `tests/docker-agent/scoped-match/` with `CHANGED_FILES` that matches one valid Dockerfile and `EXPECT_EXIT=0`.\n- Add `tests/docker-agent/scoped-no-match/` with `CHANGED_FILES` pointing to unrelated files and `EXPECT_EXIT=0` to assert SKIP.\n- Add `tests/docker-agent/no-dockerfiles/` for explicit no-target SKIP behavior if fixture directory is empty/contains non-matching files.\n- Optional `tests/docker-agent/build-check-off/` to verify command defaults (no build-check when `RUN_BUILD_CHECK=0`).\n- Optional `tests/docker-agent/build-check-skip/` with `RUN_BUILD_CHECK=1` and no `docker` binary via harness assumptions to assert SKIP message semantics (or document as environment-conditioned manual check if harness cannot stub tool removal).\n\n### Failure Modes and Error Path Assertions\n- Missing required tool: expect exit code 2 when `hadolint` absent.\n- `lint` failure from file content violations: expect exit 1 and `Fix:` line with `/docker-agent lint`.\n- `build-check` failure: expect exit 1 and `Fix:` line with `/docker-agent build-check`.\n- `CHANGED_FILES` mismatch: expect SKIP and successful exit (0).\n\n### Test Quality Rules\n- Assertion strength should validate both behavior and message (exit code plus presence of explicit `Result:` reasons).\n- Use existing harness semantics to avoid shell output brittle diffs.\n- Keep Dockerfile fixtures minimal and deterministic.\n\n## Performance Considerations\n\n### N+1 and Command Cost\n- No database access exists.\n- Avoid repeated directory scans: discover once per command run and reuse candidate set across steps.\n- Avoid nested `find` per file; do exactly one scan per invocation.\n\n### Memory/State\n- Use line-oriented strings/arrays for discovered file list; avoid holding full file contents.\n- Keep logs stream-based and on disk; avoid in-memory accumulation of full tool output for all files.\n\n### Caching and Reuse\n- Cache discovery result in a variable within invocation.\n- No cross-run cache to avoid stale results in mixed working trees.\n\n### Slow Paths\n- `find` on large monorepos and repeated `hadolint`/`docker build --check` runs are the two slow paths.\n- Build-check is explicitly opt-in to protect default run-time.\n\n### Optimization Priority\n- Low: discovery prune patterns (`.git`, `node_modules`) only.\n- Medium: avoid launching docker at all unless explicitly enabled.\n- Optional: use one `hadolint` command per file vs one aggregate command; per-file execution allows exact failure attribution and easier mapping with explicit file-level results, and is acceptable for performance with expected fixture-scale workloads.\n\n## Decision Log\n\n- Decision: Keep discovery in Bash using `find` instead of git-index enumeration.\n  - Options considered:\n    - A) `find` + extension/path filters + CHANGED_FILES narrowing.\n    - B) `git ls-files`-only discovery.\n    - C) external indexing service.\n  - Chosen approach: A.\n  - Implications: deterministic across tracked/untracked files and no extra dependency; aligns with current agent patterns.\n\n- Decision: Keep `build-check` optional and default off.\n  - Options considered:\n    - A) default off with `RUN_BUILD_CHECK=0`.\n    - B) default on with expensive execution overhead.\n    - C) remove command entirely from default flow.\n  - Chosen approach: A.\n  - Implications: faster default run; explicit opt-in controls side effects and required environment.\n\n- Decision: Use `print_result` + centralized `hadolint` log per step.\n  - Options considered:\n    - A) shared helper with per-step full log.\n    - B) per-file logs only.\n    - C) no file logs.\n  - Chosen approach: A.\n  - Implications: consistent output contract and easier debugging in downstream workflows.\n\n- Decision: Implement `CHANGED_FILES` semantics with explicit scoped match/no-match coverage.\n  - Options considered:\n    - A) only clean/issues fixtures.\n    - B) add dedicated scoped fixtures for positive and negative matches.\n    - C) no tests, trust code.\n  - Chosen approach: B.\n  - Implications: reduces regression risk for path-based discovery logic and aligns with existing architecture expectations.\n\n## Step-by-Step Implementation Plan\n\n### 1. Baseline and contract lock-in\nWhat: Read Spec 08, `.ralph/specs/01`, `.ralph/specs/02`, shared-lib file, and existing runner patterns.\nWhy: Prevents implementation drift and keeps integration assumptions explicit.\nHow: Use the already reviewed reference scripts in bash/go/gha/terra/kube and `run-scenarios` contract.\nEdge Cases: None.\nTests: No code-level tests needed in this step.\nRisks: Misreading existing defaults and introducing duplicate behavior.\n\n### 2. Create `skills/docker-agent/scripts/docker-agent.sh` scaffold\nWhat: Add executable script with shebang, `set -euo pipefail`, shared-lib source, and `RUN_LINT`, `RUN_BUILD_CHECK` defaults.\nWhy: Establishes required-agent skeleton and compatibility with all global conventions.\nHow:\n- Set `RUN_LINT=\"${RUN_LINT:-1}\"`, `RUN_BUILD_CHECK=\"${RUN_BUILD_CHECK:-0}\"`.\n- Keep file paths via `SCRIPT_DIR`, `LIB_DIR`.\n- Call `source \"${LIB_DIR}/x-agent-common.sh\"` after `set -euo pipefail`.\n- Use `setup_outdir \"docker-agent\"` and `setup_lock \"docker-agent\"` in main.\n- Parse `--fail-fast` and command early.\nEdge Cases: None.\nTests: Run syntax + `shellcheck` later.\nRisks: forgetting `setup_lock` ordering before expensive commands.\n\n### 3. Add usage/help and argument contract\nWhat: Implement `usage()` output with `lint`, `build-check`, `all` commands and universal/env knobs.\nWhy: Required by AGENT quick rules and review expectations.\nHow: Follow existing style with command section, env list (`RUN_LINT`, `RUN_BUILD_CHECK`, `MAX_LINES`, `KEEP_DIR`, `FAIL_FAST`, `CHANGED_FILES`, `TMPDIR_ROOT`), and fix hints.\nEdge Cases: help must work when dependencies are missing.\nTests: Manual `docker-agent --help` and `docker-agent -h` from a directory without Dockerfile.\nRisks: inconsistent wording with `Fix`/`Result` contract.\n\n### 4. Implement Dockerfile discovery helper\nWhat: Add `discover_dockerfiles()` that returns newline-separated Dockerfile candidates.\nWhy: Core capability for both steps and scoped behavior.\nHow:\n- Default discovery: recursive `find .` with excluded directories `.git`, `node_modules`.\n- Match filenames `Dockerfile`, `Dockerfile.*`, `*.dockerfile`.\n- If `CHANGED_FILES` set: only keep matching files from list; normalize `./` prefix consistently.\n- Sort list for deterministic command order.\nEdge Cases:\n- `CHANGED_FILES` has unrelated files.\n- Duplicate entries are deduplicated.\n- Paths with spaces are intentionally unsupported unless robust parsing is added.\nTests:\n- Add scoped fixtures for positive and negative `CHANGED_FILES` behavior.\nRisks: Overbroad `find` if prune list misses common directories.\n\n### 5. Implement `lint` step\nWhat: Add `run_lint` step to invoke `hadolint` on each discovered Dockerfile.\nWhy: Satisfies primary FR and catches static Dockerfile issues.\nHow:\n- Require `hadolint` via `need hadolint` in `main` before command execution.\n- For each Dockerfile, append output to `${OUTDIR}/lint.log`.\n- Track overall step status and call `print_result` with `Fix: resolve hadolint issues above, then re-run: /docker-agent lint`.\nEdge Cases:\n- One bad file does not hide others; include all diagnostics.\n- `hadolint` missing file path should be surfaced as command error.\n- No files discovered triggers `SKIP`.\nTests:\n- `tests/docker-agent/issues` should fail with hadolint error markers.\n- `tests/docker-agent/no-dockerfiles` should SKIP.\nRisks: command output suppression on non-failure could hide context.\n\n### 6. Implement `build-check` step\nWhat: Add `run_build_check` step to execute BuildKit lint mode on each discovered Dockerfile.\nWhy: Adds opt-in extra safety while keeping defaults cheap.\nHow:\n- If `command -v docker` fails, emit `Result: SKIP (docker not found)` with `print_result` and return success for this step.\n- For each Dockerfile, run `docker build --check -f \"$dockerfile\" .`.\n- Keep logs in `${OUTDIR}/build-check.log`.\n- Return aggregated exit status across all files.\nEdge Cases:\n- Docker daemon unavailable causes non-zero; do not hide and return failed step unless command requested skip condition.\n- Build context always project root per spec.\nTests:\n- Manual/fixture command-path `docker-agent build-check` with `RUN_BUILD_CHECK=1` on no-docker env.\n- Add explicit test for skip behavior by dependency absence where feasible.\nRisks: long runtime or daemon permission failures under CI.\n\n### 7. Implement command dispatch and all mode\nWhat: Add `main` switch for `lint`, `build-check`, `all`, and default/fail-safe handling.\nWhy: Meets command contract and orchestrates step ordering.\nHow:\n- `lint` executes `run_lint` only.\n- `build-check` executes `run_build_check` only.\n- `all` executes `run_lint` and then `run_build_check` only if `RUN_BUILD_CHECK=1`.\n- Respect `RUN_LINT` and `RUN_BUILD_CHECK` in `all` through `if` and `should_continue` gates.\n- Keep final `print_overall \"$overall_ok\"` and exit status semantics.\nEdge Cases:\n- Unknown command prints usage and exits 2.\n- `all` should not force build-check due default OFF semantics.\nTests: `tests/docker-agent/clean` and `issues` for `all` default path.\nRisks: fail-fast ordering and return code inversion.\n\n### 8. Implement `SKILL.md`\nWhat: Add `skills/docker-agent/SKILL.md` with trigger language and allowed tools.\nWhy: Enables agent-level invocation and controls in automation layers.\nHow:\n- Follow `add-x-agent.md` format.\n- Include `RUN_BUILD_CHECK=*` and `TMPDIR_ROOT=*` in `allowed-tools`.\n- Include command usage and env knobs table.\nEdge Cases: Missing key trigger phrases can reduce model matching.\nTests: Manual check via syntax and wording completeness.\nRisks: Incomplete allowed-tools list breaks runtime automation.\n\n### 9. Add scenario fixtures\nWhat: Create `tests/docker-agent/{clean,issues}` plus scoped/no-match/no-dockerfiles fixtures.\nWhy: Validates required behaviors and reduces regressions in discovery/scoping logic.\nHow:\n- `clean`: valid Dockerfile fixture, `REQUIRED_TOOLS=\"hadolint\"`.\n- `issues`: bad Dockerfile with DL3007/3009/3020 triggers.\n- `scoped-match`: set `CHANGED_FILES` to Dockerfile path and expect pass.\n- `scoped-no-match`/`no-dockerfiles`: set `CHANGED_FILES` to unrelated/empty context and expect SKIP.\n- Keep fixtures tiny and deterministic.\nEdge Cases:\n- Ensure all consumed variables are exported in scenario.env.\n- build-check command tests may be environment dependent; use command expectations carefully.\nTests: `tests/run-scenarios.sh docker-agent`.\nRisks: Over-testing command combinations can make execution fragile in minimal environments.\n\n### 10. Update `install.sh`\nWhat: Add `docker-agent` to install path and dependency checks.\nWhy: Required for discoverability and proper installation behavior.\nHow:\n- Add `docker-agent` to `SKILLS`.\n- Add optional dependency line for `hadolint` under selected skill checks.\n- Extend README snippet output with docker-agent usage sentence.\nEdge Cases:\n- Missing `docker` should not be required since build-check is opt-in.\nTests: run `sh install.sh --help` and dry-run style install check.\nRisks: local install script divergence from skill metadata if partial.\n\n### 11. Update `README.md`\nWhat: Add row and usage examples for docker-agent.\nWhy: Keeps user-facing docs aligned with supported agents.\nHow:\n- Add table row with steps: `lint, build-check`.\n- Add short usage section with command samples.\nEdge Cases: Keep table formatting stable and avoid drift from existing style.\nTests: Visual diff + grep for `docker-agent` mention.\nRisks: docs stale if options change later.\n\n### 12. Validate plan structure and metadata updates\nWhat: Run `ralph validate plan`, then adjust if checklist/format fails.\nWhy: Required pre-work gate per process instructions.\nHow: Fix any missing sections, checklist numbering, or malformed markdown.\nEdge Cases: validator may enforce exact checklist ordering requirements.\nTests: command output from `ralph validate plan`.\nRisks: spending time on repeated formatter issues.\n\n### 13. Update exploration and execute final acceptance\nWhat: Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if this implementation changes documented files, patterns, or schema and run `ralph validate work`.\nWhy: Maintains handoff quality and required acceptance gating.\nHow:\n- Already added docker-focused entries in exploration file.\n- Run `ralph validate work` and stop only on PASS.\nEdge Cases: Validation may fail on checklist completion state.\nTests: both `ralph validate plan` and `ralph validate work`.\nRisks: Work acceptance blocked by format-only mismatches.\n\n## Edge Cases and Risks\n- Discovery overreach in monorepos with many nested `.dockerignore`-like generated files.\n- Paths with spaces in `CHANGED_FILES` can mis-parse if shell loops are plain-word split.\n- `docker build --check` might require daemon/config absent in CI images.\n- `hadolint` output format changes can affect regex-free log expectations.\n- Optional-tool behavior could be misread as global failure when only `build-check` is failing but `lint` passes.\n- `SKIP` vs `FAIL` semantics must remain explicit in each branch to satisfy exit-code expectations.\n\n## Recommendations for Immediate Implementation Quality\n- Preserve command output contract exactly; use shared helpers for every result boundary.\n- Keep skip semantics explicit and deterministic (`SKIP` on no inputs, no-docker, and empty scope).\n- Use scoped fixtures in addition to base clean/issues so `CHANGED_FILES` behavior is not under-tested.\n- Keep `all` cheap by default with `RUN_BUILD_CHECK=0`.\n\n## Lessons Applied (for this plan)\n- Reuse existing fixture discipline for environment export requirements (`CHANGED_FILES`, optional knobs) before execution.\n- Prefer explicit `SKIP` messaging branches for discoverability and easier fixture assertions.\n","structuredPatch":[{"oldStart":1,"oldLines":18,"newStart":1,"newLines":18,"lines":[" ## Implementation Checklist","-- [ ] 1. Read Spec 08 plus shared-library and refactor specs to confirm contract boundaries and integration points.","-- [ ] 2. Inspect existing docker-related discovery/execution patterns in kube-agent, gha-agent, helm-agent, and install/README conventions.","-- [ ] 3. Create `skills/docker-agent/scripts/docker-agent.sh` with shared-lib sourcing, env knobs, helper structure, and CLI parser.","-- [ ] 4. Implement Dockerfile discovery that supports both repo-wide recursion and `CHANGED_FILES` filtering, with clear skip behavior.","-- [ ] 5. Implement `lint` step with per-file `hadolint` execution, aggregate full diagnostics log, and `print_result` formatting.","-- [ ] 6. Implement `build-check` step with opt-in `RUN_BUILD_CHECK`, optional `docker` detection, and `docker build --check -f <dockerfile> .` semantics.","-- [ ] 7. Implement command dispatch (`lint`, `build-check`, `all`) with `RUN_*` gating and `--fail-fast` handling.","-- [ ] 8. Add/extend test scenarios for `clean`, `issues`, and scoped/empty `CHANGED_FILES` behavior under `tests/docker-agent/`.","-- [ ] 9. Add `skills/docker-agent/SKILL.md` with triggers, usage, and allowed-tools for all knobs including `RUN_BUILD_CHECK` and optional `TMPDIR_ROOT`.","-- [ ] 10. Update `install.sh` to include `docker-agent` in `SKILLS`, dependency checks, and AGENTS/CLAUDE snippet output.","-- [ ] 11. Update `README.md` with docker-agent in the table and usage examples.","-- [ ] 12. Run `ralph validate plan` and fix any format/structure violations.","-- [ ] 13. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema","-- [ ] 14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS","+- [x] 1. Read Spec 08 plus shared-library and refactor specs to confirm contract boundaries and integration points.","+- [x] 2. Inspect existing docker-related discovery/execution patterns in kube-agent, gha-agent, helm-agent, and install/README conventions.","+- [x] 3. Create `skills/docker-agent/scripts/docker-agent.sh` with shared-lib sourcing, env knobs, helper structure, and CLI parser.","+- [x] 4. Implement Dockerfile discovery that supports both repo-wide recursion and `CHANGED_FILES` filtering, with clear skip behavior.","+- [x] 5. Implement `lint` step with per-file `hadolint` execution, aggregate full diagnostics log, and `print_result` formatting.","+- [x] 6. Implement `build-check` step with opt-in `RUN_BUILD_CHECK`, optional `docker` detection, and `docker build --check -f <dockerfile> .` semantics.","+- [x] 7. Implement command dispatch (`lint`, `build-check`, `all`) with `RUN_*` gating and `--fail-fast` handling.","+- [x] 8. Add/extend test scenarios for `clean`, `issues`, and scoped/empty `CHANGED_FILES` behavior under `tests/docker-agent/`.","+- [x] 9. Add `skills/docker-agent/SKILL.md` with triggers, usage, and allowed-tools for all knobs including `RUN_BUILD_CHECK` and optional `TMPDIR_ROOT`.","+- [x] 10. Update `install.sh` to include `docker-agent` in `SKILLS`, dependency checks, and AGENTS/CLAUDE snippet output.","+- [x] 11. Update `README.md` with docker-agent in the table and usage examples.","+- [x] 12. Run `ralph validate plan` and fix any format/structure violations.","+- [x] 13. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema","+- [x] 14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS"," "," ## Architecture Review"," "]}],"userModified":false,"replaceAll":false}}
